<td><p>73</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>102</p></td><td><p>261</p></td><td><p>351</p></td><td><p>334</p></td><td><p>1,048</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cases needing further follow-up</p></td><td><p>24</p></td><td><p>38</p></td><td><p>43</p></td><td><p>65</p></td><td><p>170</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Grand Total</p></td><td><p>322</p></td><td><p>681</p></td><td><p>905</p></td><td><p>828</p></td><td><p>2,736</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Note:<br>Figures are for England only</p><p> </p><p>Information is collected on the number of cases seen by liaison and diversion services, not the number of individuals seen. An individual may have been seen by liaison and diversion services on more than one occasion in any given time period.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-04-02T13:56:10.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104948/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104948/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104948/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-25","Speech and Language Disorders: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many children and young people in contact with liaison and diversion services have speech, language and communication needs.","true","Biography information for Geraint Davies","Swansea West","Geraint Davies","236262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104949","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-28","<p>Saudi Arabia remains a <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/saudi-arabia-human-rights-priority-country/saudi-arabia-human-rights-priority-country" target="_blank">Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office human rights priority country</a>. The UK’s recent <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/human-rights-council-40-saudi-arabia" target="_blank">Universal Periodic Review statement</a> sets out clearly the UK’s position on human rights in Saudi Arabia. We raise our concerns with the Saudi Arabian authorities using a range of Ministerial and diplomatic channels of communication.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-03-28T17:15:41.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104949/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104949/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104949/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Saudi Arabia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of alleged human rights abuses committed in (a) Saudi Arabia and (b) other countries by the Saudi Rapid Intervention Group.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104950","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-02","<p>Under the Liberty Protection Safeguards, the Approved Mental Capacity Professional criteria will be set out in regulations. Further detail on the role will also be outlined in the Statutory Code of Practice. The Government envisages professionals such as social workers, learning disability nurses, occupational therapists, psychologists and other suitable health and social care professionals could take on the role if they meet the criteria set out in regulations.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-04-02T11:42:36.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104950/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104950/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104950/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-25","Mental Capacity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what criteria will be used to determine which professionals can train to become an Approved Mental Capacity Professional; and whether those criteria will be made public.","true","Biography information for Geraint Davies","Swansea West","Geraint Davies","236263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104951","Home Office","false","2019-03-28","<p>The Government has a long-established practice of not routinely commenting on the details of individual immigration cases.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","236465 ; 236466","2019-03-28T17:12:20.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104951/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104951/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104951/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-25","Overseas Visitors: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when Saudi nationals (a) Saud al-Qahtani, (b) Maher Abdulaziz Mutreb, and (c) Thaar Ghaleb al-Harbi last visited the UK.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104952","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-04-02","<p>The Review Working Group is made up of professionals with expertise on mental capacity from across Government, the health, social care, legal and charity sectors. While there is no specialist expertise on speech and language therapy within the group, the Review has received responses from the profession as part of a Call for Evidence. These views are being fully considered as we begin to update the Code of Practice.</p><p> </p><p>There will be further opportunities for all those with an interest in the Code of Practice to provide feedback when we consult on the updated Code of Practice.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-04-02T12:59:06.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104952/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104952/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104952/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-03-25","Speech and Language Therapy: Codes of Practice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what speech and language therapy representation there is on the group working on revision of the Mental Capacity Act 2005 Code of Practice.","true","Biography information for Geraint Davies","Swansea West","Geraint Davies","236264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104953","Home Office","false","2019-03-28","<p>The Government has a long-established practice of not routinely commenting on the details of individual immigration cases.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","236464 ; 236466","2019-03-28T17:12:20.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104953/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104953/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104953/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-25","Overseas Visitors: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether Saudi nationals (a) Saud al-Qahtani, (b) Maher Abdulaziz Mutreb and (c) Thaar Ghaleb al-Harbi are currently permitted to visit the UK.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104954","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-04-01","<p>The Ministry of Justice responded to the Victims’ Commissioner’s comprehensive review of the provision of Registered Intermediaries, making these commitments: to review governance of the Witness Intermediary Scheme; to consider whether to appoint a National Lead Registered Intermediary; to publish an annual report; and to promote the role of Registered Intermediaries.</p><p>The department have delivered on these commitments and introduced improvements to governance, including the introduction of Regional Coordinator roles for exceptional Registered Intermediaries – which are more appropriate for the scheme than a National Lead. An annual report is due to be published in the summer, the scheme now has a page on Gov.uk and work is ongoing to promote the role of Registered Intermediaries.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-04-01T22:06:35.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104954/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104954/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104954/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-03-25","Victims and Witnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress has he made on implementing the recommendations contained in A Voice for the Voiceless: The Victims’ Commissioner’s Review into the Provision of Registered Intermediaries for Children and Vulnerable Victims and Witnesses, published in January 2018.","true","Biography information for Geraint Davies","Swansea West","Geraint Davies","236265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104955","Home Office","false","2019-03-28","<p>The Government has a long-established practice of not routinely commenting on the details of individual immigration cases.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","236464 ; 236465","2019-03-28T17:12:20.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104955/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104955/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-03-25","Assets: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether Saudi nationals (a) Saud al-Qahtani, (b) Maher Abdulaziz Mutreb, and (c) Thaar Ghaleb al-Harbi are currently permitted to hold assets in the UK.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104956","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-01","<p>I do not believe that the United Nations plans to relocate Rohingya refugees to Bhasan Char Island. In a press release on 25 March UN Bangladesh stated that &quot;The UN's position is to engage constructively with the Government [of Bangladesh] on Bhasan Char. We are discussing with the Government the critical protection and operational issues that should be considered before any relocations take place, in order to ensure that refugees would be able to live in safe and sustainable living conditions on Bhasan Char.&quot;</p><p> </p><p>I and other Ministers have made clear to the Government of Bangladesh, most recently in my meeting with State Minister Shahriar Alam on 27 March, that any relocation of refugees to Bhasan Char Island must be safe, dignified and in accordance with international humanitarian principles. We fully support the UN's position on relocations to Bhasan Char, which includes asking the Government of Bangladesh to allow full and detailed technical and protection assessments to be conducted of the island. The UN are examining the potential requirements, time frames and costs involved in setting up a humanitarian response on Bhasan Char.</p><p> </p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-04-01T13:21:00.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104956/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104956/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Bangladesh: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the United Nations plans to relocate Rohingya refugees from the Cox’s Bazar camps in Bangladesh to the island of Bhasan Char.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104957","Department for International Development","false","2019-04-01","<p>We have made clear to the Government of Bangladesh that any relocation of refugees to Bhasan Char island must be safe, dignified and in accordance with international humanitarian principles. We fully support the UN’s position on relocations to Bhasan Char, which asks the Government of Bangladesh to allow detailed technical and protection assessments to be conducted of the island. The UN are examining the potential requirements, time frames and costs involved in setting up a humanitarian response on Bhasan Char.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-04-01T16:22:55.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104957/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104957/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-03-25","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate he has made of the level of investment necessary for (a) the provision of clean water and sanitation and (b) flood protection to make the island of Bhasan Char habitable by Rohingya refugees.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104958","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-01","<p>​I refer the Right Honourable Member to my answer of 11 March 2019 (229694).</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-04-01T13:38:23.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104958/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104958/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Wa Lone and Kyaw Soe Oo","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his counterpart in Myanmar on the appeal against the conviction of Reuters reporters Kyaw Soe Oo and Wa Lone.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104959","Department for International Development","false","2019-04-01","<p>The Secretary of State and I have both written to the Minister of Foreign Affairs in Mozambique expressing our condolences and offering our full support. I also spoke to the Minister of Foreign Affairs on 28<sup>th</sup> March, where we discussed needs and I emphasised our continued support. Mozambique has been hardest-hit by Cyclone Idai and the number of displaced people continues to rise, with 136,000 people being sheltered in accommodation centres.</p><p> </p><p>The UK was amongst the first to respond and is the largest donor – allocating £22 million for the three countries affected. UK aid is supporting the delivery of essential relief supplies, including thousands of shelter kits, water filters, and family tents. We continue to monitor the situation closely and stand ready to provide further support if needed.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-04-01T16:26:14.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104959/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104959/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-03-25","Mozambique: Storms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in Mozambique on that country’s humanitarian needs as a result of Cyclone Idai.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104960","Department for International Development","false","2019-04-01","<p>The Secretary of State and I have both written to the Minister of Foreign Affairs and International Trade in Zimbabwe expressing our condolences and offering our full support. The UK was amongst the first to respond and is the largest donor – allocating £22 million to the response across the three countries affected. While the impact of Cyclone Idai has not been as severe in Zimbabwe as in Mozambique, the situation remains serious and 4,500 people have been displaced. In Zimbabwe, UK aid is providing support for health, child protection, and water, sanitation, and hygiene in the worst-affected areas. DFID is also supporting the provision of emergency latrines and sanitation equipment. We continue to monitor the situation closely and stand ready to provide further support if needed.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-04-01T16:27:10.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104960/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104960/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-03-25","Zimbabwe: Storms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in Zimbabwe on that country’s humanitarian needs as a result of Cyclone Idai.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104961","Treasury","false","2019-03-28","<p>Departments responsible for the Police, Firefighters’, NHS, Local Government and Armed Forces pension schemes have made the necessary regulatory changes arising from the Walker v. Innospec Limited judgment. Departments responsible for the Teachers’ and Civil Service pension schemes are in the process of doing so.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2019-03-28T13:18:27.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104961/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104961/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-03-25","Public Sector: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 19 April 2018 to Question 135229 on Public Sector: Pensions, what progress has been made by responsible Departments in implementing the necessary regulatory changes arising from the Walker v. Innospec Limited judgement.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","236560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104962","Department for International Development","false","2019-04-01","<p>The Secretary of State and I have both written to the Minister of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation in Malawi expressing our condolences and offering our full support. UK staff on the ground are supporting the response with the Government of Malawi. The UK was amongst the first to respond and is the largest donor – allocating £22 million to the response, including £3.4million to Malawi. In Malawi, our support is providing 65,000 people with emergency shelter, 150,000 people with food assistance, 250,000 with access to clean water and sanitation, and 130,000 people with access to health services. We continue to monitor the situation closely and stand ready to provide further support if needed.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-04-01T16:49:25.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104962/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104962/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-03-25","Malawi: Storms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her counterpart in Malawi on that country’s humanitarian needs after Cyclone Idai.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104963","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-01","<p>The assistance the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) can provide to British nationals abroad is set out in the publication: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/support-for-british-nationals-abroad-a-guide" target="_blank">Support for British nationals abroad: A Guide</a>. It includes information on what we can do in cases of death abroad (page 21), for victims of torture and mistreatment (page 17), and for those in detention or prison overseas (page 19). It also includes information on who the FCO can help (page 6). In all cases, the level and type of assistance we offer is tailored to the individual circumstances of each case</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>​</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-04-01T14:11:55.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104963/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104963/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","British Nationals Abroad: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his Department's guidance is on responding to the (a) death, (b) torture and (c) imprisonment of British citizens abroad.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","236561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104964","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-01","<p>The assistance the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) can provide to British nationals abroad is set out in the publication: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/support-for-british-nationals-abroad-a-guide" target="_blank">Support for British nationals abroad: A Guide</a>. It includes information on what we can do in cases of death abroad (page 21), for victims of torture and mistreatment (page 17), and for those in detention or prison overseas (page 19). It also includes information on who the FCO can help (page 6). In all cases, the level and type of assistance we offer is tailored to the individual circumstances of each case</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>​</p><p> </p><p>​</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-04-01T14:28:14.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104964/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104964/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","British Nationals Abroad: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what criteria his Department uses to assess whether consular assistance is provided after the (a) death, (b) torture and (c) imprisonment of a British citizen abroad.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","236562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104965","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-02","<p>Foreign and Commonwealth Office staff who are posted overseas at regular intervals during their career may claim Continuity of Education Allowance towards the cost of standard tuition fees plus boarding at UK schools, up to the applicable ceiling per term for a junior or senior pupil, and subject to eligibility criteria.</p><p>The current ceilings are (per term, based on a three term school year):</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Senior Boarder</p></td><td><p>£10,570</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Senior Day</p></td><td><p>£7,400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Junior Boarder</p></td><td><p>£9,291</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Junior Day</p></td><td><p>£6,504</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Where school fees exceed the termly ceiling, staff are required to meet the difference.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2019-04-02T16:08:06.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104965/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104965/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Private Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 3 December 2018 to Question 196148 on Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Private Education, what the current maximum level of financial subsidy per child is that can be claimed by staff in his Department to support the private education of their children at UK schools.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104966","Scotland Office","false","2019-04-02","<p>I have regular discussions with the Scottish Government on a range of issues, including those which span both devolved and reserved matters; the Scottish Government has powers to tackle poverty through the devolution of skills, education, health and employment programmes.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2019-04-02T16:39:49.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104966/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104966/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2019-03-25","Poverty: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what recent discussions he has had with the Scottish Government on reducing child poverty levels in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Hugh Gaffney","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Hugh Gaffney","236563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104967","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-02","<p>192 of the 541 children did so.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2019-04-02T16:12:21.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104967/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104967/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Private Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the corrected Answer of 18 March 2019 to Question 196150 on Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Private Education, how many of the 541 children whose private education in UK schools was supported by his Department in 2016-17 received the maximum level of financial subsidy available per child.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104968","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-01","<p>​The Sino-British Joint Declaration describes Hong Kong's high degree of autonomy, and its executive, legislative and independent judicial powers.</p><p>The Foreign Secretary publishes a comprehensive assessment of the situation in Hong Kong every six months. The most recent report, covering the period July – December 2018, was laid before Parliament on 27 March.</p><p>Hong Kong's success is underpinned by its high degree of autonomy, independent judiciary and respect for fundamental rights and freedoms enshrined in the Joint Declaration. However recent events have demonstrated increasing pressure on this high degree of autonomy and Hong Kong's rights and freedoms. It remains the British Government's view that, for Hong Kong's future success, it is essential that Hong Kong enjoys, and is seen to enjoy, the full measure of its high degree of autonomy and rule of law as set out in the Joint Declaration and enshrined in the Basic Law, in keeping with the commitment to 'One Country, Two Systems'.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","236476","2019-04-01T13:45:13.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104968/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104968/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Hong Kong: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what definition the Government has of the high degree of autonomy that Hong Kong is supposed to exercise under the terms of Article 2 of the Basic Law that came into effect in 1997;  and what assessment he has made of whether Hong Kong enjoys that high degree of autonomy.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104969","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-01","<p>​The Sino-British Joint Declaration describes Hong Kong's high degree of autonomy, and its executive, legislative and independent judicial powers.</p><p>The Foreign Secretary publishes a comprehensive assessment of the situation in Hong Kong every six months. The most recent report, covering the period July – December 2018, was laid before Parliament on 27 March.</p><p>Hong Kong's success is underpinned by its high degree of autonomy, independent judiciary and respect for fundamental rights and freedoms enshrined in the Joint Declaration. However recent events have demonstrated increasing pressure on this high degree of autonomy and Hong Kong's rights and freedoms. It remains the British Government's view that, for Hong Kong's future success, it is essential that Hong Kong enjoys, and is seen to enjoy, the full measure of its high degree of autonomy and rule of law as set out in the Joint Declaration and enshrined in the Basic Law, in keeping with the commitment to 'One Country, Two Systems'.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field","236475","2019-04-01T13:45:13.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104969/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104969/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104969/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Hong Kong: Judiciary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what definition his Department has of executive, legislative and independent judicial power that Hong Kong is supposed to enjoy under the terms of Article 2 of the Basic Law that came into effect in 1997; and what assessment he has made of whether Hong Kong currently holds those powers.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104970","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-28","<p>Diplomatic protection is a mechanism under international law according to which a State may seek to secure reparation for injury to one of its nationals, on the basis that the second State has committed an internationally wrongful act against the national. The general threshold conditions required in order for a State to consider whether or not to exercise diplomatic protection are generally accepted to be: (i) the commission of an internationally wrongful act; (ii) the exhaustion of local remedies; and (iii) proof of nationality, or, in the case of a dual national, predominant nationality. Diplomatic protection is rarely used. Any request for diplomatic protection would be assessed on a case-by-case basis.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-03-28T17:17:27.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104970/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104970/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104970/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","British Nationals Abroad: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will set out the criteria used to assess whether diplomatic protection is provided following the torture or imprisonment of a British citizen whilst overseas.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","236564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104971","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-01","<p>The UK Government remains concerned about the disappearance of Dong Samuel and Ezbon Idri following their abduction in Nairobi in 2017, reportedly by the South Sudanese authorities. Their disappearance is part of a deeply troubling pattern of harassment and intimidation of civic actors in South Sudan, and the repression of freedom of expression by the authorities. The British Government continues to press the Government of South Sudan for the release of all political prisoners in accordance with the 12 September peace agreement. The Government of South Sudan's failure to comply with this provision of the agreement calls into question their commitment to achieving a meaningful peace.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-04-01T13:48:46.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104971/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104971/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104971/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Dong Samuel Lauk and Aggrey Ezbon Idri","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterparts in South Sudan and Kenya on the detention of human rights activists Dong Samuel Luak and Aggrey Ezbon Idri.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104972","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-01","<p>Officials at our High Commission in Maputo have raised the issue of the detention of Amade Abubacar with Mozambican officials at national and local level. Our High Commissioner to Maputo also raised the issue with the provincial government in Cabo Delgado Province on 17 January.</p><p>Mr Abubacar was initially held in military detention. However, following enquiries by officials, Mr Abubacar has been formally charged and moved into custody in a civilian prison. We continue to follow his case closely.</p><p>The UK remains strongly committed to freedom of the press and the protection of journalists.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-04-01T13:55:22.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104972/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104972/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104972/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Amade Abubacar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in Mozambique on the detention of journalist Amade Abubacar.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104973","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-01","<p>​We were deeply saddened by the killing of Ahmed Hussein-Suale and offered our condolences to his family and friends. Our High Commissioner in Ghana has made representations to the Government of Ghana, including through a statement made alongside other European Union Heads of Missions in Ghana. We continue to urge the authorities to ensure that there is a full investigation into the matter. As the Foreign Secretary set out on 18 January those responsible must face justice. Our High Commissioner is closely monitoring events following the beating and detention of a Ghanaian Times journalist, Malik Sullemana in 2018. We are in contact with the Ghanaian Times and the Ghanaian Police, and have urged the authorities to conclude their investigation into the matter.</p><p>The UK is committed to the promotion of media freedom and the protection of journalists worldwide. The Foreign Secretary has launched an international campaign to end the climate of impunity and mobilise a consensus behind the protection of journalists. In the coming year and beyond, we are going to increase the global spotlight on media freedom as an important issue.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-04-01T13:59:49.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104973/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104973/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104973/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Ahmed Hussein-Suale Divela and  Malik Sullemana ","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in Ghana on (a) the murder of journalist Ahmed Hussein-Suale Divela and (b) the beating and detention of journalist Malik Sullemana in that country.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104974","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-01","<p>​The UK remains deeply concerned about the arrest, detention and sentencing of political actors, including the sentencing of 26 opposition supporters on 24 March, arrested during the 26 January protests. On 21 March, the UK and Austria made a joint statement at the UN Human Rights Council on the human rights situation in Cameroon, including a call for timely, fair trial or release of political detainees. On 13 February I underlined that trials, including of Opposition leader Maurice Kamto, must follow due process, and that freedom of speech and political expression are integral to a democratic society. We encourage all Commonwealth member states to adhere to the values in the Commonwealth Charter, including the protection and promotion of civil, political economic social and cultural rights, and the inalienable right of individuals to participate in democratic processes. Officials are in regular contact with the Commonwealth Secretariat and member states to discuss these issues<em>. </em></p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2019-04-01T14:04:26.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104974/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104974/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104974/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Cameroon: Demonstrations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in Cameroon on the recent sentencing of 26 people for illegal gathering and demonstration in that country; and what assessment he has made of whether those convictions are consistent with the terms of the Commonwealth Charter.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104975","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-02","<p>We are deeply concerned about reports that human rights lawyers and activists are being detained in China.</p><p>I raised Wang Quanzhang's case with the Chinese Government during my visit last July. My colleague the Foreign Secretary also raised Wang Quanzhang's case last July, when he met Chinese State Councillor Wang Yi.</p><p>The Foreign Secretary also released a statement on 29 January 2019, which expressed concern over the sentencing of both Wang Quanzhang and Liu Feiyue, and urged the Chinese government to ensure fundamental civil and political rights are protected, in line with China's constitution and its international commitments.</p><p>Since then, senior diplomats in Beijing, including the British Ambassador to China, have met with Wang Quanzhang's family. A British diplomat also attempted to attend Mr Wang's trial on 26 December, though was denied entry to the courtroom. We continue to monitor his case.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-04-02T15:20:44.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104975/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104975/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104975/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","Liu Feiyue and Wang Quanzhang","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Chinese counterpart on the recent jail sentences given to (a) journalist and human rights activist Liu Feiyue and (b) human rights lawyer Wang Quanzhang.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","236481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104976","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-03-28","<p>Diplomatic protection is a mechanism under international law according to which a State may seek to secure reparation for injury to one of its nationals, on the basis that the second State has committed an internationally wrongful act against the national. As a consequence, diplomatic protection is rarely used. Any request for diplomatic protection would be assessed on a case-by-case basis. Diplomatic protection is distinct from consular assistance where a State provides help to its nationals who find themselves in trouble in another State. The assistance the Foreign and Commonwealth Office can provide to British nationals abroad is set out in the publication: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/support-for-british-nationals-abroad-a-guide" target="_blank">Support for British nationals abroad: A Guide.</a></p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-03-28T17:20:01.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104976/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104976/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1104976/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-03-25","British Nationals Abroad: Diplomatic Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what criteria is applied to a decision on whether a British citizen receives consular assistance or diplomatic protection.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","236565"
